> @Walker Reynolds 1.  I saw on one of your YT video that you suggested Highbyte for IIoT solutions. Isn't that just another application as well? Why do you want to build on top that and not PI? Coming back to your couch analogy, is highbyte replaceable anytime if needed with something else? 
> 2. How do you even suggest something like highbyte which is in release 1.0 to big clients? I do not see a scenario where they'd approve it as their primary data repository. Maybe some very small cap companies will use it. But that's all.
@nadream you are not building on top of it -- highbyte is on the edge as an application (building asset frames/objects/udts to structure the data) and serves as an open broker if used as the UNS.  HighByte can be used as both a UNS AND an Edge Asset frame builder with MQTT client/transmitter.  Pi cannot.  Pi does not support failover to another broker (see my most recent post in #unified-namespace ) so it does not support the architecture you need to leverage as the UNS in the middle but it does provide the functionality to structure the information and data it creates for publishing back into the namespace (asset frames).  Highbyte, Ignition, FactoryStudio et al have application functionality AND can serve as the open hub.  More and more, we are using a standalone broker for the UNS (HiveMQ is our preferred right now) but we lose any form of abstraction functionality in the UNS when we do that.

