If you're tied to Rockwell, take a look at CompactLogix 5380.  The pricing is much more competitive on this generation.  The 600kb models, even with motion and safety, are quite good value.  One used to spend 3x more to get these features in a base processor.  These offer so much more than the Micro/MicroLogix models for  not much more.  While they lack IIoT connectivity, these have excellent driver support.

While not necessarily a bad product, I feel like the Micro800 was created/acquired for small machine builders to satisfy customers that demand AB at lowest possible cost.  It provides customers with the name but not what they normally would associate with the name.  Unfortunately, they have so many shortcomings in terms of connectivity and software.  For example, it's basically pointless to offer a PLC with EtherNet/IP interface without Class 1 CIP support.  Outside of HMI/SCADA, most fieldbus connections are used to exchange I/O.  It can do this over ModbusTCP, but not EtherNet/IP.  

@Brian Pribe makes a good point that it may be worthwhile to explore alternatives than trying to make the Micro800 work.

